{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Some palaeontology studies present data acquired with an incident neutron beam, which can be combined with X-ray microtomography.",
    "Arguably the oldest form of tomography utilized within paleontology (Zdansky 1938), serial sectioning tomography is a destructive analysis which entails the progressive cutting, grinding and/or polishing of a fossil specimen, with intermittent image capture used to reveal its internal structure (Alkemper and Voorhees 2001).",
    "The scale and precision of serial sectioning varies greatly between applications, ranging from sparse blocks, slices or thin sections that provide cross sectional overviews of specimen structure (e.g., Ørvig (1980)), to high resolution tomographic images which can be fully interrogated with volume image analysis techniques.",
    "Conventionally, serial sectioning has been undertaken using manual mechanical sectioning (Sutton et al. 2001), though dedicated facilities have emerged which automate the process (Mehra and Maloof 2018).",
    "Further to this, broad ion beam / focused ion beam scanning electron microscopy (BIB/FIB-SEM) tomography, which uses an ion beam (i.e., Gallium, Argon) and paired SEM to periodically ablate and image a sample surface extends the concept of serial sectioning towards the nano-domain, facilitating the detailed reconstruction of microfossil structure (Mehra and Maloof 2018; Fellah et al. 2021)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
